  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I be sure people won't steal my idea during a pitch?",
  "response": "Protecting your idea during a pitch can be challenging, but there are several steps you can take to minimize the risk of theft:\n\n1. **Non-Disclosure Agreements (NDAs):** Ask potential partners or investors to sign an NDA before your pitch. This legal document outlines that they cannot disclose or use your idea without your permission.\n\n2. **Limit Information Sharing:** Share only the necessary details about your idea. Focus on the problem you are solving, your unique value proposition, and why you need investment or partnership, rather than revealing sensitive technical details.\n\n3. **Intellectual Property (IP) Protection:** Consider filing for patents or trademarks to protect your invention or brand. Even provisional patents can provide some level of protection while you seek funding or partnerships.\n\n4. **Document Everything:** Keep detailed records of your idea development process, including dates, drafts, and communications. This can help establish your claim to the idea if needed.\n\n5. **Research Your Audience:** Know who you are pitching to and their reputation in the industry. This can help you identify trustworthy individuals or companies.\n\n6. **Build Trust:** Establish a rapport with your audience before sharing sensitive information. People are less likely to steal ideas from those they trust.\n\n7. **Pitch with Confidence:** Present your idea as a work in progress, emphasizing your journey and the unique insights you've gained. This can make your concept feel more customized and less likely to be appropriated.\n\n8. **Seek Feedback Instead of Investment:** Frame your pitch as a request for feedback rather than an outright investment. This can make it easier to engage without fear of theft.\n\n9. **Network Wisely:** Build relationships in the industry that can lead to respectful partnerships. Often, people are more inclined to respect ideas within a trusted network.\n\n10. **Be Prepared for Reactions:** Understand that not all investors will engage positively. Stay professional and detached if you sense someone is not respecting your idea.\n\nWhile no strategy can guarantee absolute protection, combining these steps can significantly reduce the risk of your idea being stolen during a pitch.",
